{"id":"1010.1726","submitter":"Philip Matchett Wood","authors":"Philip Matchett Wood","title":"Universality and the circular law for sparse random matrices","comments":"Published in at http://dx.doi.org/10.1214/11-AAP789 the Annals of\n  Applied Probability (http://www.imstat.org/aap/) by the Institute of\n  Mathematical Statistics (http://www.imstat.org)","journal-ref":"Annals of Applied Probability 2012, Vol. 22, No. 3, 1266-1300","doi":"10.1214/11-AAP789","report-no":"IMS-AAP-AAP789","categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The universality phenomenon asserts that the distribution of the eigenvalues\nof random matrix with i.i.d. zero mean, unit variance entries does not depend\non the underlying structure of the random entries. For example, a plot of the\neigenvalues of a random sign matrix, where each entry is +1 or -1 with equal\nprobability, looks the same as an analogous plot of the eigenvalues of a random\nmatrix where each entry is complex Gaussian with zero mean and unit variance.\nIn the current paper, we prove a universality result for sparse random n by n\nmatrices where each entry is nonzero with probability $1/n^{1-\\alpha}$ where\n$0<\\alpha\\le1$ is any constant. One consequence of the sparse universality\nprinciple is that the circular law holds for sparse random matrices so long as\nthe entries have zero mean and unit variance, which is the most general result\nfor sparse random matrices to date.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 8 Oct 2010 16:03:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 10 Oct 2012 05:28:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-10-11"}
